EXPLANATION – Matter in bolded italics is new; matter between brackets [omitted material] is material to be omitted.
AN ACT relating to criminal procedure; authorizing a court to waive the
requirement that the Division of Parole and Probation of the
Department of Public Safety make a presentence investigation and
report under certain circumstances; providing that a failure by the
Chief Parole and Probation Officer to submit a presentence
investigation and report before a sentencing hearing is not grounds for
an order of contempt under certain circumstances; revising
requirements relating to the disclosure of a presentence investigation
and report to a defendant; and providing other matters properly relating
thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law requires the Division of Parole and Probation of the Department of Public
2 Safety to make a presentence investigation and report to the court on certain defendants. (NRS
3 176.135) Section 1 of this bill authorizes the court to waive this requirement if the defendant
4 and the prosecuting attorney stipulate to waive the requirement and the court approves the
5 stipulation. Section 3 of this bill makes a conforming change to clarify that if the court waives
6 the requirement, the court may grant probation without receiving the presentence investigation
7 and report.
8 Existing law requires the Division to: (1) include a psychosexual evaluation as part of a
9 presentence investigation and report under certain circumstances; and (2) arrange for a
10 psychosexual evaluation of each defendant to whom this requirement applies. (NRS 176.135,
11 176.139) Existing law requires a person who conducts a psychosexual evaluation of a
12 defendant to provide a copy of the written report of the results of the evaluation to the
13 Division. (NRS 176.139) Section 1 provides that if the Division does not receive a copy of the
14 written report of the results of the evaluation at least 3 days before the sentencing hearing, a
15 failure by the Chief Parole and Probation Officer to submit the presentence investigation and
16 report before the sentencing hearing is not grounds for an order of contempt.
17 In general, existing law requires the Division to disclose the factual content of the report
18 of any presentence investigation made by the Division to the prosecuting attorney, the counsel
19 for the defendant, the defendant and the court not later than 14 calendar days before the

